        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "Apparently PHP's OO Mysqli adapter class does not correctly handle large integers when it returns the last insert ID.\n\nSee the following note http:\/\/ca2.php.net\/manual\/en\/mysqli.insert-id.php#84625 on PHP's website. I'll quote it here, as well:\n{quote}\nWatch out for the oo-style use of $db->insert_id. When the insert_id exceeds 2^31 (2147483648) fetching the insert id renders a wrong, too large number. You better use the procedural mysqli_insert_id( $db ) instead.\n\n[EDIT by danbrown AT php DOT net: This is another prime example of the limits of 32-bit signed integers.]\n{quote}\n\nSo, we should be able to work around the problem by replacing:\n\n{code}\n    public function lastInsertId($tableName = null, $primaryKey = null)\n    {\n        $mysqli = $this->_connection;\n        return (string) $mysqli->insert_id;\n    }\n{code}\n\nwith\n\n{code}\n    public function lastInsertId($tableName = null, $primaryKey = null)\n    {\n        $mysqli = $this->_connection;\n        return (string) mysqli_insert_id($mysqli);\n    }\n{code}\n\nI'll test this and submit a patch when ready.\n\n"
        },
